title: Killing of Cartel Boss Sets Off Chaos in Mexico, and Trump Has a New Plan for Tariffs
partialText: Plus, a shooting at Mar-a-Lago.

title: Drug Lord ‘El Mencho’ Was Killed in Mexico. What’s Next for the Cartel He Led?
partialText: The death of Nemesio Oseguera Cervantes dealt a major blow to the Jalisco New Generation Cartel, but few believe it spells the end for the powerful group.

title: What to Know About the Killing of ‘El Mencho’
partialText: The Mexican government has killed Nemesio Oseguera Cervantes, the longtime leader of one of Mexico’s most powerful gangs, the Jalisco New Generation Cartel.

title: For Iran’s Rulers, Refusing U.S. Demands Is a Risk Worth Taking
partialText: The government in Tehran sees capitulating to Washington’s demands on uranium enrichment and ballistic missiles as riskier to its survival than going to war, analysts say.

title: Trump Considers Targeted Strike Against Iran, Followed by Larger Attack
partialText: The top negotiators plan to meet in Geneva on Thursday for last-ditch talks, debating a new proposal that could create an off-ramp as two carrier groups massed within striking distance of Iran.

title: The Next Conflict
partialText: We’re looking at the potential for a U.S. attack on Iran.

title: Trump’s Challenge to Free Market Capitalism
partialText: Stakes in private companies. Handshake deals with chief executives. The president’s economic policy has drifted far from principles that long defined the Republican Party. Is it capitalism at all?

title: Why the Supreme Court Struck Down Trump’s Tariffs
partialText: Our reporter Ann E. Marimow describes the rationale of the Supreme Court’s 6-to-3 ruling to strike down President Trump’s sweeping tariffs.

title: Top Fed Official Sees Little Effect on Rate Outlook From Supreme Court’s Tariff Ruling
partialText: Christopher J. Waller, a Federal Reserve governor, said he would support a pause in rate cuts in March if the labor market continued to show signs of stabilizing.

title: What’s Happened Since the Supreme Court’s Tariff Ruling
partialText: After the Trump administration’s punishing tariffs were invalidated, the president said he would impose new tariffs using a different authority. It’s been a whirlwind.

title: Pizzoccheri Was Prominent at Winter Olympics in Italy
partialText: Pizzoccheri, a hearty buckwheat pasta, graced restaurant menus and the athletes’ cafeterias. A chef hopes it can put a spotlight on the valley where it comes from.

title: Fact-Check: Trump’s Latest Claims on Jobs, Inflation and Crime
partialText: Trends on jobs, inflation and crime that began before Donald Trump retook office continued, largely unabated, in his first year back.

title: As Trump Touts Economic Gains, Many Workers Still Feel the Pinch
partialText: President Trump says that he has brought down inflation, but families are still struggling to pay bills and plan for the future.

title: When Faced With Claims of Racism, Trump Points to His Black Friends
partialText: President Trump has often invoked his unnamed Black friends, or name-checked celebrities and athletes, when asked to discuss anything related to Black voters.

title: Judges Grow Angry Over Trump Administration Violating Their Orders
partialText: At least 35 times since August, federal judges have ordered the administration to explain why it should not be punished for violating their orders in immigration cases.

title: Backed by Anthropic, a Super PAC Begins an Ad Blitz in Support of A.I. Regulation
partialText: The ads by Public First Action, which started airing on Monday, are part of an escalating political war over artificial intelligence before the midterm elections.

title: ‘A.I. Literacy’ Is the New Drivers’ Ed at This Newark School
partialText: Teachers say they want to equip high school students to drive artificial intelligence, rather than be mere passengers steered by chatbots.

title: Supreme Court to Weigh Oil-Industry Effort to End a Major Climate Suit
partialText: The case could have significant bearing on a range of other lawsuits brought against the fossil fuel industry by cities and states across the country.

title: Supreme Court Considers Fate of Docks and Other Assets Seized by Cuba in 1960
partialText: Amid rising tensions with Cuba, the Trump administration is backing lawsuits that would allow Americans to get compensation for property confiscated by Fidel Castro’s regime.

title: The Ukrainian Bureaucrat Working to Squeeze Russia’s War Machine
partialText: Vladyslav Vlasiuk has spent the past four years pressing Western allies to squeeze the Russian economy through more sanctions. He hopes that 2026 will be the tipping point.

title: EU Support for Ukraine Stumbles as Hungary Looks to Delay Aid
partialText: Hungary said that it would block both the latest sanctions package on Russia and a financial aid package to Kyiv worth about $106 billion.

title: The Zero Units Fought for the C.I.A. in Afghanistan. In the U.S., They’re Living in Fear.
partialText: A shooting in Washington, D.C., threw their immigration status into jeopardy — and brought attention to a long-hidden dimension of America’s war.

title: Democrats Consider Breaking a Taboo in Washington State: A Millionaires Tax
partialText: The state where Jeff Bezos and Bill Gates made fortunes might have progressive social policies, but its resistance to an income tax is similar to conservative states. That might change.

title: BAFTAs 2026: The Best and Worst Moments
partialText: Alan Cumming forced fishy British snacks onto movie stars. Paddington Bear presented an award. And a racist slur and swearing.

title: BAFTAs Winners 2026: ‘One Battle After Another’ Wins Best Film, Besting ‘Sinners’
partialText: Paul Thomas Anderson’s comedy drama won six awards at the British equivalent of the Oscars. The best actor choice, however, was a surprise.

title: The Human Cost of the Trump Administration’s War on Science
partialText: The ripple effects of cutting H.I.V. research funding.

title: ‘The Pitt’ Is the Most Patriotic Show on Television
partialText: An emergency room that’s a mirror.

title: Architecture Prize Responds After Tom Pritzker’s Epstein Ties Surface
partialText: A Pritzker Prize statement cited the award’s independence after Mr. Pritzker, who directs the foundation behind the award, resigned as chairman of the Hyatt Corporation.

title: France Summons U.S. Ambassador Over Comments on Activist’s Killing
partialText: Charles Kushner, President Trump’s envoy to Paris, was called in after the State Department cited “violent radical leftism” in the beating death of Quentin Deranque, 23.

title: World’s 50 Best Restaurants Draws Criticism After Choosing to Hold Ceremony in Abu Dhabi
partialText: The World’s 50 Best Restaurants will give out its awards this year in a country that has been accused of human rights violations.

title: Cities May Be ‘Evolutionary Training Grounds’ For Spotted Lanternflies
partialText: Living in urban China may have given the insects the traits they needed to thrive in the United States, a new study suggests.
